Certainly! Below is an example of an Express route handler `greet` written in TypeScript that reads a "name" query parameter and responds with a small HTML page displaying "Hello, {name}!" in a heading.

First, make sure you have the necessary dependencies installed:

```bash
npm install express typescript @types/express ts-node-dev --save-dev
```

Then, create a `greet.ts` file with the following content:

```typescript
import express from 'express';

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.get('/greet', (req, res) => {
    const name = req.query.name as string | undefined;
    if (!name) {
        return res.status(400).send('Please provide a "name" query parameter.');
    }

    const htmlResponse = `
        <!DOCTYPE html>
        <html lang="en">
        <head>
            <meta charset="UTF-8">
            <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
            <title>Greet</title>
        </head>
        <body>
            <h1>Hello, ${name}!</h1>
        </body>
        </html>
    `;

    res.send(htmlResponse);
});

app.listen(port, () => {
    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${port}`);
});
```

To run this TypeScript file, you can use the following command:

```bash
npx ts-node-dev greet.ts
```

This will start a server on `http://localhost:3000`. When you navigate to `http://localhost:3000/greet?name=YourName`, it will display an HTML page with "Hello, YourName!" in a heading. If the "name" query parameter is not provided, it will return a 400 status code with an error message.

